    <!-- Add Activity -->
     <activity>
        <statement>

            <p>
                A farmer places grains of rice on a board such that:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>1</m> grain is placed on the first square,</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>2</m> grains on the second square,</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>4</m> grains on the third square,</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>and the number of grains keeps doubling on each square.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                The board has 9 squares arranged in a <m>3 \times 3</m> grid.
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Write the number of grains on each of the <m>9</m> squares.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Find the total number of grains on the board.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Describe the pattern you observe.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Extension:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li>
                        <p>If the board had <m>20</m> squares, would it be efficient to add all the grains one by one? Explain.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Suggest a faster method for finding the total number of grains.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Guided Exploration:</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                Let the total number of grains on the <m>9</m> squares be:
            </p>

            <p>
                <m>S_9 = 1 + 2 + 4 + 8 + \dots + 2^8</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Multiply both sides by <m>2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Write an expression for <m>2S_9</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Compare <m>S_9</m> and <m>2S_9</m>. What do you notice?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Subtract the two expressions. Which terms remain?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Hence determine the value of <m>S_9</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Generalising:</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                If the first term is <m>a</m> and the common ratio is <m>r</m>, then:
            </p>

            <p>
                <m>S_n = a + ar + ar^2 + \dots + ar^{n-1}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Task:</term> Repeat the process above to obtain a general formula for <m>S_n</m>.
            </p>

        </statement>
        
     </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

